facts by analyzing early promotional fantasies about the phonograph as a new kind of speaker and detailing initiatives to deploy it as a pedagogical tool to heighten literary experience. Through historically-grounded interpretations of Dickens impersonators to recitations of Tennyson to T.S. Eliot's experimental readings of "The Waste Land" and of a great variety of voices and media in between, this first critical history of the earliest literary sound recordings offers an unusual perspective on the transition from the Victorian to modern periods and sheds new light on our own digitally mediated relationship to the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEnglish literaturexAudio adaptationsxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and technologyxHistory. 0aOral interpretationxHistory. 0aPhonographxHistory. 0aSound recordingsxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAudiotext.  aGramophone.  aLiterature.  aMedia.  aPhonograph.  aPoetics.  aSound Recording.  aSpoken Word.  aVictorian.  aVoice.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503609716zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503609716423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503609716.jpg  a978-3-11-069228-0  SUP Complete eBook-Package 20